<h1>From Henry Bouquet</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Camp near Reas Town 14th July 1758</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Having been out to visit the Roads I received this afternoon your two Letters of yesterday.</p>
<p>I am obliged to you for the notice of the Sad Accident happened to your Men. This Warning may prevent more effectually than orders the Carelesness and disobedience of our People.</p>
<p>The General recommands me to Send frequent Partys to harrass the Ennemies at home; I have actually four out, besides the Indians Sent by Col. Byrd:<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> If you Should think proper to Send Some of your brisk young fellows under the Care of a prudent officer, we could keep them busy at home.</p>
<p>As I am entirely unacquainted wth this Country I would look upon it as a favour, if you would let me Know your opinion, upon the Possibility of Sending a Strong Party to the Indian Settlements upon the Ohio; If their houses and familis were in danger, I would think it a great inducemt for them to provide for their immediate defence and leave to the french their own quarrels to fight.</p>
<p>Before the General could be acquainted wth your New dress, he has approved it extremely upon a hint I gave him Some time ago.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
<p>It takes very well here, and thank God, we See nothing but Shirts and Blanketts, &amp;ca.</p>
<p>The Convoys fall So thick upon us that we have no time to do any thing but to lodge them and I am obliged to beg the assistance of your Second Compy of artificers for a few days after they have cut the Road, and build two Logg houses half Way, for a detachment and Some Stores if wanted.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0003-ptr">3</a></p>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-05-02-pb-0287">[287]</span>
<p>The General desires you would Send a Party to reconnoitre Braddocks Road, and begin to clear a few miles, repairing the Bridges &amp;ca.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0004" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0004-ptr">4</a></p>
<p>We have not a Soul idle in the CampThe Field officers being themselves overseers.</p>
<p>We shall have Carrying horses, few Waggons and Still less Bagage.</p>
<p>Our new comers Cherokee, are gone away after having Stolen our goods. It is a great humiliation for us to be obliged to Suffer the repeated Insolence of Such Rascals; I think it would be easier to make Indians of our White men, than to coax that damned Tanny Race.</p>
<p>You will receive the Generals Standing Orders which we have read this morning to the Troops here.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0005" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0005-ptr">5</a></p>
<p>I am at a Loss how to Settle the Money between the two Provinces; If you could tell me the way, I would be obliged to you.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0006" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0006-ptr">6</a> My Respects to Mr Glen &amp; Col. Byrd I am most Sincerely Your most obedt humble Servant</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Henry Bouquet</p>
</div>
<div class="postscript">
<p>You have forgot the Letter from Capt. Dagworthy I write to Col. Mercer.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0007" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0007-ptr">7</a></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0231-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>Bouquet may have been referring here to Forbess letter of 27 June urging him to keep scouting parties out toward the Ohio, which Bouquet did not receive until this date, 14 July. For a party of one hundred that Bouquet sent out on 8 July, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0211" class="document">Bouquet to GW, 8 July</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0199&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-05-02-0199-fn-0006#GEWN-02-05-02-0199-fn-0006" class="document">GW to Bouquet, 3 July (first letter), n.6</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>The 2d company of artificers under the command of Capt. John Posey from the 2d Virginia Regiment was one of the three companies in the party commanded by Lt. Col. George Mercer which began to cut the road from Fort Cumberland to Raystown on 8 July. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0213" class="document">GW to Bouquet, 9 July</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>On 16 July GW responded that he did not have the tools to undertake the work on Braddocks Road. When Capt. John Dagworthy and his men were ordered to discontinue work on a road from Fort Cumberland to Fort Frederick and on 18 July returned to Fort Cumberland, GW gave the Marylanders tools to 300 men of the 2d Virginia Regiment and on 22 July sent them up Braddocks Road under the command of Maj. William Peachey. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0239" class="document">GW to Bouquet, 19 July</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0234&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-05-02-0234-fn-0001#GEWN-02-05-02-0234-fn-0001" class="document">GW to Francis Halkett, 16 July 1758, n.1</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0006">6</a>

   <p>GW informed Bouquet on 16 July that the rate of exchange of colonial currency between the two provinces was fixed by law.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0007-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0231-fn-0007">7</a>

   <p>Bouquet is referring to the (missing) letter from John Dagworthy to
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-05-02-pb-0288">[288]</span>
which GW responded on 13 July and supposedly enclosed in his letter to Bouquet of 13 July. Bouquets letter to George Mercer has not been found.</p>

</div>
</div>
